            <div class=3D"collapsibleContainer">

            <div class=3D"collapseButton">
                <h3 class=3D"top">
                    <span class=3D"plus"></span>=20
                    <span><a name=3D"permutation"></a>What is a permutation=
?</span>
                </h3>
                <div style=3D"display: none;">
                    <p>A permutation is an arrangement of all or part of a =
<a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DSet">
		    set</a> of objects, <i>with</i> regard to the order of the arrangemen=
t.</p>
            <p>For example, suppose we have a set of three letters: A, B, a=
nd C.=20
	    We might ask how many ways we can arrange 2 letters from that set. Eac=
h=20
	    possible arrangement would be an example of a permutation. The complet=
e list of=20
	    possible permutations would be: AB, AC, BA, BC, CA, and CB.</p>
            <p>When statisticians refer to permutations, they use a specifi=
c=20
	    terminology. They describe permutations as <i>n</i> distinct objects t=
aken <i>r</i>
	    at a time. Translation: <i>n</i> refers to the number of objects from =
which the=20
	    permutation is formed; and <i>r</i> refers to the number of objects us=
ed to=20
	    form the permutation. Consider the example from the previous paragraph=
. The=20
	    permutations were formed from 3 letters (A, B, and C), so <i>n</i> =3D=
 3; and=20
	    each permutation consisted of 2 letters, so <i>r</i> =3D 2.</p>
            <p>Note that AB and BA are considered to be two permutations, b=
ecause=20
	    the order in which objects are selected matters. This is the key=20
	    distinction between a=20
        <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3D=
combination">combination</a>
        and a permutation.
        A combination focuses on the selection of objects <i>without</i>
	    regard to the order in which they are selected. A permutation, in cont=
rast,=20
	    focuses on the arrangement of objects <i>with</i> regard to the order =
in which=20
	    they are arranged. Bottom line: AB and BA represent two permutations, =
but only one combination.</p>
            <p>For an example that counts permutations, see <a href=3D"http=
s://stattrek.com/online-calculator/combinations-permutations#problem1">
		    Sample Problem 1</a>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class=3D"collapseButton">
                <h3>
                    <span class=3D"plus"></span>=20
                    <span><a name=3D"combination"></a>What is a combination=
?</span>
                </h3>                   =20
                <div style=3D"display: none;">
                    <p>A combination is a selection of all or part of a <a =
href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DSet">
		    set</a> of objects, <i>without</i> regard to the order in which objec=
ts are=20
	    selected.</p>
            <p>For example, suppose we have a set of three letters: A, B, a=
nd C.=20
	    We might ask how many ways we can select 2 letters from that set. Each=
 possible=20
	    selection would be an example of a combination. The complete list of p=
ossible=20
	    selections would be: AB, AC, and BC.</p>
            <p>When statisticians refer to combinations, they use a specifi=
c=20
	    terminology. They describe combinations as <i>n</i> distinct objects t=
aken <i>r</i>
	    at a time. Translation: <i>n</i> refers to the number of objects from =
which the=20
	    combination is formed; and <i>r</i> refers to the number of objects us=
ed to=20
	    form the combination. Consider the example from the previous paragraph=
. The=20
	    combinations were formed from 3 letters (A, B, and C), so <i>n</i> =3D=
 3; and=20
	    each combination consisted of 2 letters, so <i>r</i> =3D 2.</p>
            <p>Note that AB and BA are considered to be one combination, be=
cause=20
	    the order in which objects are selected does not matter. This is the k=
ey=20
	    distinction between a combination and a=20
        <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3D=
Permutation">permutation</a>.=20
        A combination focuses on the selection of objects <i>without</i>
	    regard to the order in which they are selected. A permutation, in cont=
rast,=20
	    focuses on the arrangement of objects <i>with</i> regard to the order =
in which=20
	    they are arranged. Bottom line: AB and BA represent two permutations, =
but only one combination.</p>
            <p>For an example that counts the number of combinations, see <=
a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/online-calculator/combinations-permutations#=
problem2">
		    Sample Problem 2</a>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class=3D"collapseButton">
                <h3>
                    <span class=3D"plus"></span>=20
                    <span><a name=3D"differ"></a>How do you count the numbe=
r of combinations?</span>
                </h3>                      =20
                <div style=3D"display: none;">
                    <p>A <b>combination</b> is a selection of all or part o=
f a set of objects, <i>without</i>
	    regard to the order in which they were selected.  This means that XYZ =
is
	    considered the same combination as ZYX. </p>
        <p>The number of combinations of <i>r</i> objects that can be selec=
ted from a set of <i>n</i> objects is=20
		    denoted by <sub>n</sub>C<sub>r</sub>. And the formula for computing t=
hat number is:</p>
            <p style=3D"text-align:center;"><sub>n</sub>C<sub>r</sub> =3D n=
(n - 1)(n=20
			    - 2) ... (n - r + 1)/r! =3D n! / r!(n - r)!=20
		    </p>
            <p><b>Note:</b> In the formula above, n! refers to n factorial,=
 where n! is equal to=20
                <i>n</i>(<i>n</i>-1)(<i>n</i>-2)&nbsp;...&nbsp;(3)(2)(1).</=
p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class=3D"collapseButton">
                <h3>
                    <span class=3D"plus"></span>=20
                    <span><a name=3D"differ"></a>How do you count the numbe=
r of permutations?</span>
                </h3>                      =20
                <div style=3D"display: none;">
                    <p>A <b>permutation</b> is a selection of all or part o=
f a set of objects, <i>with</i>
	    regard to the order in which they were selected.  This means that XYZ =
is
	    considered a different permutation than ZYX.</p>
        <p>The number of permutations of <i>r</i> objects that can be selec=
ted from a set of <i>n</i> objects is=20
		    denoted by <sub>n</sub>P<sub>r</sub>. And the formula for computing t=
hat number is:</p>
            <p style=3D"text-align:center;"><sub>n</sub>P<sub>r</sub> =3D n=
(n - 1)(n=20
			    - 2) ... (n - r + 1) =3D n! / (n - r)!=20
		    </p>
            <p><b>Note:</b> In the formula above, n! refers to n factorial,=
 where n! is equal to=20
                <i>n</i>(<i>n</i>-1)(<i>n</i>-2)&nbsp;...&nbsp;(3)(2)(1).</=
p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class=3D"collapseButton">
                <h3>
                    <span class=3D"plus"></span>=20
                    <span><a name=3D"differ"></a>What is the difference bet=
ween a combination and a permutation?</span>
                </h3>                      =20
                <div style=3D"display: none;">
                    <p>The distinction between a <a href=3D"https://stattre=
k.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DCombination">
		    combination </a>and a <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dict=
ionary?definition=3DPermutation">permutation</a>
	    has to do with the sequence or order in which objects appear. A combin=
ation=20
	    focuses on the selection of objects <i>without</i> regard to the order=
 in which=20
	    they are selected. A permutation, in contrast, focuses on the arrangem=
ent of=20
	    objects <i>with</i> regard to the order in which they are arranged.</p=
>
            <p>For example, consider the letters A and B. Using those lette=
rs,=20
	    we can create two 2-letter permutations - AB and BA. Because order is =
important=20
	    to a permutation, AB and BA are considered different permutations. How=
ever, AB=20
	    and BA represent only one combination, because order is not important =
to a=20
	    combination.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

        <div class=3D"collapseButton">
            <h3>
                <span class=3D"plus"></span>=20
                <span><a name=3D"Enotation"></a>What is E Notation?</span>
            </h3>                   =20
            <div style=3D"display: none;">
                <p>The Combinations and Permutations Calculator uses E nota=
tion to express very=20
                    large numbers. E notation is a way to write numbers tha=
t are too large or=20
                    too small to be concisely written in a decimal format.<=
/p>
                        <p>With E notation, the letter E represents "times =
ten raised to the=20
                    power of". Here is an example of a number written using=
 E notation:</p>
                        <p style=3D"text-align:center;">3.02E+12 =3D 3.02 *=
 10<sup>12</sup> =3D 3,020,000,000,000</p>
                <p></p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class=3D"collapseButton">
            <h3>
                <span class=3D"bottom plus"></span>=20
                <span><a name=3D"Enotation"></a>How accurate is this calcul=
ator?</span>
            </h3>                   =20
            <div style=3D"display: none;">
                <p>When the number of combinations or permutations is displ=
ayed as an ordinary integer, the result is exact.
                    When the number of combinations or permutations is disp=
layed using
                    <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?d=
efinition=3De-notation">E notation</a>, the result is not exact; but it is =
a
                    very good approximation, accurate to 16 decimals.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        </div>

