            <ol style=3D"margin-left:-1rem;">
	    <li>
            <p><a name=3D"problem1"></a>How many 3-digit numbers can be for=
med from the digits=20
		    1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, and 7, if each digit can be used only once?</p>
		    <p><b>Solution:</b></p>
		    <p>The solution to this problem involves counting the number of permu=
tations of 7=20
		    distinct objects, taken 3 at a time. The number of permutations of <i=
>n</i> distinct=20
		    objects, taken <i>r</i> at a time is:</p>

		    <p style=3D"text-align:center;">  =20
			    <sub>n</sub>P<sub>r</sub> =3D n! / (n - r)!
			    <br>
			    <sub>7</sub>P<sub>3</sub> =3D 7! / (7 - 3)! =3D 7! / 4! =3D (7)(6)(5=
) =3D 210
		    </p>
		   =20
	    <p>Thus, 210 different 3-digit numbers can be formed from the digits 1=
, 2, 3, 4,=20
	    5, 6, and 7.  To solve this problem using the=20
	    <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/online-calculator/combinations-permuta=
tions#Calculator">Combination and Permutation Calculator</a>, do the follow=
ing:</p>
	        <ul>
	            <li>Enter "3" for "Subset size".</li>
	            <li>Enter "7" for "Set size".</li>
	            <li>Click the "Calculate" button.</li>
	        </ul>
	    <p>The answer, 210, is displayed in the "Permutations" textbox, as sho=
wn below.</p></li>
    </ol>
   =20
